Beatriz Valero de Urquía
So each tense has different endings
It’s a lot, I know, I think verbs are the hardest thing about spanish
Nov 10, 2017, 11:54 AM
Beatriz Valero de Urquía
And then verbs that end in -er like leer (to read) or comer (to eat) are
Yo leo- como
Tu lees-comes
El lee-come
Nosotros leemos-comemos
Vosotros leéis-coméis
Ellos leen-comen
Nov 10, 2017, 11:53 AM
Beatriz Valero de Urquía
Verbs that end in -ar like cantar (sing) or saltar (to jump) are
Yo canto/salto
Tu cantas - saltas
El canta- salta
Nosotros cantamos-saltamos
Vosotros cantáis-saltáis
Ellos cantan-saltan
Nov 10, 2017, 11:52 AM
Beatriz Valero de Urquía
So, vivir, (to live) that ends the same would be
Yo vivo
Tu vives
El vive
Nosotros vivimos
Vosotros vivís
Ellos viven
Nov 10, 2017, 11:51 AM
Beatriz Valero de Urquía
So basically
You have to find the verb in infinitive, like the general one
Escribir-to write
And when you have that there are 3 types of verbs depending if they end in “ar”, “er” or “ir”
And then you take the first part of the infinitive and the terminations for each form depending in how they end
Like escribir
You take “escrib”
And then add termination

Beatriz Valero de Urquía
So, verb to write (escribir)
Yo escribo (I write)
Tu escribes (you write)
El/Ella escribe (she/he write)
Nosotros escribimos (we write)
Vosotros escribís (you write)
Ellos/ellas escriben (they write)

Aman Ganglani
That's fantastic! Yep I'm part of the committee. It's fun but it takes a lot of time. The rest of them are fun, I spent most of my time last year with EWB and wanted to try new stuff out. Surprisingly, despite the degree name, I don't do a lot of biology. The course is focused on the engineering applications to medicine, so it's a lot of instrumentation (think of the physics in hospitals, all the imaging machines + prosthetics for example). Most of what I work on is electrical/mechanical engineering. The end goal is to build crap and then hand it over to a doctor/nurse who will presumably do something with it. That is interesting! I'm guessing that's the introduction of electricity? I'm thinking of massive transport improvements? I like hanging around non stem people from time to time. I think we spend so long around other engineers that we barely get a chance to interact with the rest of UCL. If your free tomorrow or Thursday between 12-2, wanna grab lunch? Don't worry about it if your busy, I hope today went well for you :)
